---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-switzerland', text: 'Leaving Swiss Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'swiss-expectations', text: 'Meeting Swiss Expectations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'returning-to-switzerland', text: 'Returning to Switzerland', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Bupa Global Review', href: '/providers/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'Best Europe Insurance', href: '/best/europe-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Premium Insurance', href: '/best/premium-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best German Expat Insurance', href: '/best/german-expat-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'service', header: 'Service Quality' },
  { key: 'globalNetwork', header: 'Global Network' },
  { key: 'swissCoverage', header: 'Swiss Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', service: 'Excellent', globalNetwork: 'Excellent', swissCoverage: 'Add-on (expensive)', price: 'CHF 300/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', service: 'Premium', globalNetwork: 'Excellent', swissCoverage: 'Add-on (expensive)', price: 'CHF 350/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', service: 'Very Good', globalNetwork: 'Strong', swissCoverage: 'Add-on', price: 'CHF 280/mo' },
  { provider: 'SWICA Global', service: 'Excellent (Swiss)', globalNetwork: 'Good', swissCoverage: 'Included', price: 'CHF 400/mo' },
  { provider: 'CSS International', service: 'Good (Swiss)', globalNetwork: 'Limited', swissCoverage: 'Included', price: 'CHF 350/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Swiss Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Swiss expats. Find coverage that meets Swiss quality expectations for destinations worldwide."
  headline="Best Insurance for Swiss Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Switzerland has some of the world's best (and most expensive) healthcare. Here's how to maintain quality coverage when you move abroad."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/swiss-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Swiss expats have high healthcare expectations—and the budget to match. Your insurance needs depend on maintaining quality while potentially enjoying lower costs abroad. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Swiss expats. Premium service quality, excellent global networks, comprehensive coverage matching Swiss expectations.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Top-tier coverage with outstanding service. Meets the highest expectations.</li>
    <li><strong>SWICA Global:</strong> Swiss insurer with international products. Familiar brand, Swiss service standards, includes Swiss coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Strong European coverage at competitive prices. Good option for European destinations.</li>
    <li><strong>CSS International:</strong> Another Swiss option with international coverage. Swiss service, familiar processes.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Swiss Coverage Warning"
    description="Many international policies exclude Switzerland due to high costs, or charge substantial premiums for Swiss coverage. If you plan to visit Switzerland regularly, confirm coverage terms and costs upfront."
    buttonText="Compare Options"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-switzerland">Leaving Swiss Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    Switzerland has mandatory health insurance (Grundversicherung/LAMal). Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>Mandatory Insurance Ends</h3>
  <p>
    When you deregister from Switzerland (Abmeldung), your obligation to have Swiss mandatory insurance ends. You should notify your Krankenkasse and cancel your policy. You cannot maintain Swiss Grundversicherung while living abroad.
  </p>

  <h3>Supplementary Insurance (Zusatzversicherung)</h3>
  <p>
    If you have Zusatzversicherung (private supplementary coverage), check with your insurer. Some Swiss insurers offer international options that can continue your supplementary coverage abroad. Others require cancellation.
  </p>

  <h3>Coordination with Destination</h3>
  <p>
    Switzerland has bilateral agreements with EU/EFTA countries. If you're moving within this area, social security coordination may affect your coverage. Moving outside these agreements means you need fully independent international coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Timing</h3>
  <p>
    Arrange international insurance before canceling Swiss coverage. There should be no gap—Swiss penalties for insurance gaps don't apply once you've left, but being uninsured is still risky.
  </p>

  <h2 id="swiss-expectations">Meeting Swiss Expectations</h2>
  <p>
    Swiss expats are accustomed to excellent healthcare. Here's what to look for in international coverage:
  </p>

  <h3>Service Quality</h3>
  <p>
    Switzerland has among the world's best healthcare service. International policies should offer:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>24/7 multilingual support (German, French, Italian, English)</li>
    <li>Fast claims processing (Swiss efficiency expectations)</li>
    <li>Direct billing at quality hospitals</li>
    <li>Medical case management for complex situations</li>
    <li>Second opinion services</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Coverage Levels</h3>
  <p>
    Swiss healthcare has no annual limits—everything is covered. International plans should offer:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>High or unlimited coverage limits (minimum CHF 5 million)</li>
    <li>Comprehensive benefits including mental health</li>
    <li>Preventive care and wellness</li>
    <li>Emergency evacuation and repatriation</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Hospital Standards</h3>
  <p>
    Swiss hospitals are modern and efficient. Look for insurers with networks that include:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>JCI-accredited facilities</li>
    <li>Private or semi-private room options</li>
    <li>Access to specialists without excessive waiting</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">The Cost Reality</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Swiss healthcare costs are among the world's highest. International insurance will likely cost less abroad—but adding Switzerland as a coverage region significantly increases premiums. Consider whether you need Swiss coverage or can pay out-of-pocket during visits.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global offers premium international coverage that meets Swiss quality expectations. Their Platinum tier provides unlimited coverage, comprehensive benefits, and excellent service. Networks include top hospitals worldwide.
  </p>

  <p>
    Multilingual support is available including German and French. Swiss coverage can be added but is expensive due to Swiss healthcare costs.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Swiss expats who want premium coverage matching Swiss standards.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa Global offers top-tier international coverage with outstanding service quality. Their premium tiers match Swiss healthcare expectations with unlimited coverage and comprehensive benefits.
  </p>

  <p>
    Service is excellent, claims processing is efficient, and the network includes world-class facilities. Swiss coverage available at additional cost.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Swiss expats who want the absolute best coverage available.
  </p>

  <h3>SWICA Global</h3>
  <p>
    SWICA is one of Switzerland's major health insurers, offering international products for Swiss expats. The advantage is familiar Swiss service standards, German/French/Italian language support, and included Switzerland coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    International networks are adequate but may not match Cigna or Bupa in some regions. Pricing is higher but includes Swiss coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Swiss expats who prefer Swiss service and need seamless Switzerland coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care offers strong European coverage at competitive prices. Good option for Swiss expats moving within Europe. Service quality is good, and multilingual support is available.
  </p>

  <p>
    Swiss coverage can be added. Networks are strong in Europe and adequate globally.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Swiss expats in Europe who want comprehensive coverage at reasonable prices.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Premium Options"
    description="Swiss expats typically prioritize quality over price. Compare top-tier plans to find the right combination of service, coverage, and Swiss access."
    buttonText="Get Premium Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="returning-to-switzerland">Returning to Switzerland</h2>
  <p>
    Returning to Swiss healthcare requires arranging new Grundversicherung:
  </p>

  <h3>Mandatory Insurance Requirement</h3>
  <p>
    Within 3 months of returning to Switzerland, you must arrange Grundversicherung (basic mandatory insurance). This is non-negotiable—everyone living in Switzerland must be insured.
  </p>

  <h3>No Underwriting for Grundversicherung</h3>
  <p>
    Swiss law requires Krankenkassen to accept everyone for Grundversicherung regardless of health status. Pre-existing conditions cannot be excluded from basic coverage. This is a significant advantage of the Swiss system.
  </p>

  <h3>Zusatzversicherung</h3>
  <p>
    Supplementary insurance involves underwriting. If you had conditions develop while abroad, they may be excluded or result in higher premiums for Zusatzversicherung.
  </p>

  <h3>Transition Period</h3>
  <p>
    Keep your international insurance active until Swiss coverage begins. The 3-month window gives you time, but arranging coverage early ensures no gaps.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I keep Swiss insurance abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">No. Grundversicherung requires Swiss residence. Some insurers offer international products, but these are separate from the mandatory system.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Why is Swiss coverage expensive?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Swiss healthcare costs are among the world's highest. International insurers charge premium prices for Swiss coverage because claims there are expensive.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Do I need Swiss coverage for visits?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Short visits may be manageable without specific Swiss coverage—you could pay out-of-pocket or use emergency provisions. For frequent visits, Swiss coverage is worth considering.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is SWICA or Cigna better?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">SWICA offers Swiss familiarity and included Swiss coverage. Cigna has stronger global networks. Choose based on how much Swiss coverage matters to you.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about my AHV/AVS pension?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Swiss pension rights are maintained. Contact your AHV/AVS office about voluntary contributions if you want to maximize your pension while abroad.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Will international coverage match Swiss quality?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Premium international plans (Cigna Platinum, Bupa Premium) match Swiss service standards. Lower tiers may feel like a downgrade. Choose accordingly.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Swiss expats should prioritize quality international coverage that matches their healthcare expectations. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> and <strong>Bupa Global</strong> premium tiers deliver Swiss-level service worldwide. <strong>SWICA Global</strong> suits those who prefer Swiss insurers and need seamless Swiss coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Allianz Care</strong> offers good value for European destinations without the highest costs.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before leaving, understand the costs of Swiss coverage on international policies. You may save money by excluding Switzerland and paying out-of-pocket during visits—or Swiss coverage may be worth the premium for peace of mind.
  </p>

</PageShell>
